{"id":"2007.04478","submitter":"Andrzej Dudek","authors":"Patrick Bennett, Ryan Cushman and Andrzej Dudek","title":"Closing the Random Graph Gap in Tuza's Conjecture Through the Online\n  Triangle Packing Process","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A long-standing conjecture of Zsolt Tuza asserts that the triangle covering\nnumber $\\tau(G)$ is at most twice the triangle packing number $\\nu(G)$, where\nthe triangle packing number $\\nu(G)$ is the maximum size of a set of\nedge-disjoint triangles in $G$ and the triangle covering number $\\tau(G)$ is\nthe minimal size of a set of edges intersecting all triangles. In this paper,\nwe prove that Tuza's conjecture holds in the Erd\\H{o}s-R\\'enyi random graph\n$G(n,m)$ for all range of $m$, closing the gap in what was previously known.\n(Recently, this result was also independently proved by Jeff Kahn and Jinyoung\nPark.) We employ a random greedy process called the online triangle packing\nprocess to produce a triangle packing in $G(n,m)$ and analyze this process by\nusing the differential equations method.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 8 Jul 2020 23:50:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-10"}
