{"id":"2007.04658","submitter":"Che-Ming Li","authors":"Chia-Kuo Chen, Shih-Hsuan Chen, Ni-Ni Huang, Che-Ming Li","title":"Identifying genuine quantum teleportation","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 104, 052429 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.104.052429","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Quantum teleportation is a method for utilizing quantum measurements and the\nmaximally entangled Einstein-Podolsky-Rosen (EPR) pair to transmit an unknown\nquantum state. It is well known that all entangled states demonstrate so-called\n\"nonclassical teleportation\" that cannot be simulated by the seminal classical\nmeasure-prepare strategy. Herein, we propose a new benchmark which reveals that\nnot all nonclassical teleportations are truly quantum-mechanical. Rather, there\nexists a more robust classical-teleportation model, which includes the\nmeasure-prepare mimicry as a special case, that can describe certain\nnonclassical teleportations. Invalidating such a general classical model\nindicates genuine quantum teleportation wherein both the pair state and the\nmeasurement are truly quantum-mechanical. We prove that EPR steering empowers\ngenuine quantum teleportations, rather than entanglement. The new benchmark can\nbe readily used in practical experiments for ensuring that genuine quantum\nteleportation is implemented. The results presented herein provide strict\ncriteria for implementing quantum-information processing where genuine quantum\nteleportation is indispensable.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 9 Jul 2020 09:32:29 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 13 Jul 2020 12:52:39 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 19 Aug 2020 09:10:25 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 30 Nov 2021 05:53:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-01"}
